An earthquake measuring 5.7 has killed at least 11 people and injured more than 120 in northwestern Tanzania. The quake which hit Saturday afternoon was felt in neighbouring Rwanda, Burundi, Uganda and Kenya. According to the US Geological Survey, the epicentre of the 1227 GMT (3.27pm local time) quake was about 25 kilometres east of the north western town of Nsunga on the border of Lake Victoria. In Uganda, the earthquake was most felt in central and the southern parts of the country including the capital Kampala. Earthquakes are fairly common in the Great Lakes region but are almost always of low intensity. An earthquake measuring 5.7 has killed at least 11 people and injured more than 120 in northwestern Tanzania.The quake which hit Saturday afternoon was felt in neighbouring Rwanda, Burundi, Uganda and Kenya.According to the US Geological Survey, the epicentre of the 1227 GMT (3.27pm local time) quake was about 25 kilometres east of the north western town of Nsunga on the border of Lake Victoria.In Uganda, the earthquake was most felt in central and the southern parts of the country including the capital Kampala.Earthquakes are fairly common in the Great Lakes region but are almost always of low intensity.